          <text class="word" x="8" y="12">{word2.toLocaleLowerCase()}</text>
          <text class="word" x="10" y="17">{word3.toLocaleLowerCase()}</text>
          <text class="word" x="12" y="22">{word4.toLocaleLowerCase()}</text>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div
        x-data="{ activeAccordion: '', setActiveAccordion(id) { this.activeAccordion = (this.activeAccordion == id) ? '' : id } }"
        class="md:col-span-2 md:w-3/4 mx-auto"
      >
        <p
          class="text-2xl tracking-tight text-center font-medium text-black mb-4"
        >
          Story
        </p>
        <div x-data="{ id: $id('accordion') }" class="text-gray-500 text-left">
          <p class="mb-4">
Elara, a scholar of some renown, possessed an a priori understanding of avian behavior. She knew, without ever observing it, that a bird's song was an expression of joy.  This conviction fueled her current project: a comprehensive study of the common sparrow.  Her colleagues scoffed, calling her methods retrograde. They insisted on field observation, data collection, the scientific method. Elara, however, believed intuition was a powerful tool, and her indefatigable spirit wouldn't allow her to be deterred by their criticisms. She argued that true understanding came from within, a deep resonance with the subject matter, not from cold, sterile measurements. She felt a connection to the sparrows, a sense of shared existence, that no amount of data could replicate.
          </p>
          <div
            @click="setActiveAccordion(id)"
            :class="activeAccordion==id ? 'hidden' : ''"
            class="cursor-pointer text-opacity-70 underline hover:text-accent-900"
          >
            [Continue Reading]
          </div>
          <div x-show="activeAccordion==id" x-collapse="">
            <p>
She spent countless hours in her small, cluttered office, listening to recordings of sparrow songs. Stacks of books on ornithology surrounded her, mostly unopened. She preferred to close her eyes and simply listen, letting the melodies wash over her. One morning, a particularly vibrant warble filled the air from the speaker. It wasn't just a sound; it was a feeling, a pure, unadulterated expression of happiness. Elara smiled. Her theory was correct. She just knew it. The scoffing of her colleagues faded into the background noise of her life. She had heard the truth, not with her ears, but with her soul. And that, she believed, was far more valuable.
            </p>
            <div
              @click="setActiveAccordion('')"
              :class="activeAccordion==id ? '' : 'hidden'"
              class="cursor-pointer text-opacity-70 underline hover:text-accent-900 mt-4"
            >
              [Hide]
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
